      "en": "A derivative is the slope of a local linear approximation. On a motion graph it reads velocity near one time; on a loss landscape it reads how loss responds near one parameter value. Positive sensitivity means increasing that parameter slightly tends to increase loss; negative means increasing it slightly tends to decrease loss; near zero means locally flat along that coordinate. None is a global guarantee. A curve can turn, a nonsmooth point can lack one derivative, and a step far outside the local neighborhood can contradict the tangent prediction."
